  │    - For any finite collection \(U_1, \dots, U_n \in \tau\), the intersection \(\bigcap_{i=1}^n U_i\) is in \(\tau\).
  │ 
  │ 2. The answer defines a closed subset of a topological space as a subset whose complement is an open set.
  │ 
  │ 3. The answer explicitly states a list of “basic properties” that hold in any topological space. Among these properties, the following must be included (presented in an equivalent form):
  │    - The empty set and the whole space are closed.
  │    - The intersection of an arbitrary collection of closed sets is closed.
  │    - The union of any finite collection of closed sets is closed.
  │    - A set is open if and only if its complement is closed.
