  │ A **topological space** is a pair \((X, \tau)\) consisting of a set \(X\) and a collection \(\tau\) of subsets of \(X\), called **open sets**, that must satisfy three axioms: (1) the empty set and \(X\) itself belong to \(\tau\); (2) the union of any collection of sets in \(\tau\) is again in \(\tau\); and (3) the intersection of any finite collection of sets in \(\tau\) is also in \(\tau\) [Source: data\local\topology_notes.md]. These axioms allow the definition of fundamental concepts such as **continuity** (a function is continuous if the preimage of every open set is open), **compactness** (every open cover has a finite subcover), and **connectedness** (the space cannot be split into two disjoint non‑empty open sets) [Source: data\local\topology_notes.md].
